    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n    <title>Topological Sort</title>\n    <style>\n        body {\n            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n        }\n        .text-explanation {\n            font-size: 18px;\n            margin-bottom: 20px;\n        }\n        .text-example {\n            font-size: 18px;\n            margin-bottom: 20px;\n        }\n        .text-demo {\n            font-size: 18px;\n            margin-bottom: 20px;\n        }\n        .button {\n            background-color: #4CAF50;\n            color: #fff;\n            padding: 10px 20px;\n            border: none;\n            border-radius: 5px;\n            cursor: pointer;\n        }\n        .button:hover {\n            background-color: #3e8e41;\n        }\n    </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <h1>Topological Sort</h1>\n    <div class=\"text-explanation\">\n        Topological Sort is a linear ordering of vertices in a directed acyclic graph (DAG) such that for every directed edge (u, v), vertex u comes before v in the ordering.\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"text-example\">\n        Suppose we have a simple directed acyclic graph with 5 vertices:\n        <img src=\"graph.jpg\" alt=\"Directed Acyclic Graph\">\n        Each vertex is assigned a weight, and edges are weighted according to their weights.\n        The topological sort of this graph is:\n        <ul>\n            <li>1</li>\n            <li>2</li>\n            <li>3</li>\n            <li>4</li>\n            <li>5</li>\n        </ul>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"text-demo\">\n        Let's consider a more complex directed acyclic graph with 7 vertices:\n        <img src=\"graph2.jpg\" alt=\"Complex Directed Acyclic Graph\">\n        The topological sort of this graph is:\n        <ul>\n            <li>1</li>\n            <li>2</li>\n            <li>3</li>\n            <li>4</li>\n            <li>5</li>\n            <li>6</li>\n            <li>7</li>\n        </ul>\n    </div>\n    <button class=\"button\">Try it out</button>\n    <script>\n        function topologicalSort(graph, vertices) {\n            const visited = new Array(vertices.length).fill(false);\n            const ordering = [];\n\n            function dfs(vertex) {\n                visited[vertex] = true;\n                for (const neighbor of graph[vertex]) {\n                    if (!visited[neighbor]) {\n                        dfs(neighbor);\n                    }\n                }\n                ordering.push(vertex);\n            }\n\n            for (let i = 0; i < vertices.length; i++) {\n                if (!visited[i]) {\n                    dfs(i);\n                }\n            }\n\n            return ordering.reverse();\n        }\n\n        const graph = {\n            0: [1, 2],\n            1: [2, 3],\n            2: [3, 4],\n            3: [4, 5],\n            4: [5],\n            5: []\n        };\n\n        const vertices = Object.keys(graph);\n\n        const topologicalSortOrder = topologicalSort(graph, vertices);\n        console.log(\"Topological Sort Order:\", topologicalSortOrder);\n\n        const graph2 = {\n            0: [1, 2, 3],\n            1: [2, 3, 4],\n            2: [3, 4, 5],\n            3: [4, 5, 6],\n            4: [5, 6],\n            5: [6],\n            6: []\n        };\n\n        const vertices2 = Object.keys(graph2);\n\n        const topologicalSortOrder2 = topologicalSort(graph2, vertices2);\n        console.log(\"Topological Sort Order (second graph):\", topologicalSortOrder2);\n    </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
